value of the @rel provides th=
e sole association with _all_ the semantic
details for the link (both proto=
col-level and domain-level).

The semantic details are spelled out in human=
-readable formz9in some
external Out-of-band document) and it is up to the =
developer to code this
human-readable information into the client before re=
leasing the client
&quot;into the wild&quot;. The response message contains no templa=
tes/forms, no
indications of transclusion, safety, or idempotency; that inf=
ormation is
always in the documentation alone.

For example, if the resourc=
e at the other end of the link allows one or
more optional arguments to be =
included, this is in documentation and not
indicated in the message. If the=
 resource expects a DELETE or PUT to be
used along w/ a body, the details o=
n determining which (DELETE or PUT is
used) is in the documentation. If the=
re are required elements when sending
a body, it&#39;s in the documentation, an=
d so forth.

